  "text": "Kubernetes/kubernetes does NOT use controller-runtime's `SetupWithManager`/`Reconciler` pattern. Instead it has its own controller registration framework. The key flow is:\n\n1. **`controller.Interface`** (staging/src/k8s.io/controller-manager/controller/interfaces.go): Defines the base interface all controllers implement, with optional `Debuggable` and `HealthCheckable` extensions.\n\n2. **`ControllerDescriptor` + `InitFunc`** (cmd/kube-controller-manager/app/controllermanager.go:419-429): Each controller is wrapped in a `ControllerDescriptor` carrying its name, aliases, feature gates, and an `InitFunc` \u2014 the equivalent of `SetupWithManager`. The `InitFunc` signature is `func(ctx, ControllerContext, controllerName) (controller.Interface, bool, error)`.\n\n3. **Registration** via `NewControllerDescriptors()` (controllermanager.go:495-593): All controllers are registered by calling `register()` with their descriptor (e.g., `newDeploymentControllerDescriptor()`). Individual descriptor constructors live in domain files like `apps.go` and `core.go`.\n\n4. **Wiring into the reconcile loop**: `Run()` \u2192 `CreateControllerContext()` \u2192 `StartControllers()` \u2192 `StartController()` which calls each descriptor's `InitFunc`. The init functions (e.g., `startDeploymentController` in apps.go) instantiate the controller, then launch it with `go controller.Run(ctx, concurrency)`.\n\n5. **`controller_names.go`** defines canonical controller name constants used in registration.\n\n6. **`helper.go`** and **`controllercontext.go`** in staging/src/k8s.io/controller-manager/app/ provide the generic `IsControllerEnabled` check and the base `ControllerContext` struct reused by cloud-provider controller managers.",
